{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}} {{Infobox museum | name =Virasat-e-Khalsa | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image =Khalsa Heritage Memorial 176 Edit.jpg | imagesize = | caption = Virasat-e-Khalsa | alt = Virasat-e-Khalsa | map_type = India Punjab | map_caption = | map_alt = | map_size = | coordinates = {{Coord|31|13|55|N|76|30|09|E|display=inline,title}} | established = {{Start date|df=yes|1999|04|13}} | dissolved = | location = Anandpur Sahib | type = Sikh museum | collection = | director = | president = | curator = | owner = Punjab Government | publictransit = | car_park = Open | network = | website = http://virasat-e-khalsa.net/ |founder = }}
'''Virasat-e-Khalsa''' ({{lang-pa|ਵਿਰਾਸਤ-ਏ-ਖਾਲਸਾ}}) is a museum of [[Sikhism]], located in the holy town, [[Anandpur Sahib]], near [[Chandigarh]], the capital of the state of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]. The museum celebrates 500 years of the [[Sikh history]] and the 300th anniversary of the [[Khalsa|birth of Khalsa]], based on the scriptures written by the tenth and last human guru, [[Guru Gobind Singh]].
==Structure== There are two complexes at each side of a ravine, connected by a ceremonial bridge: *The smaller western complex includes an entrance plaza, an auditorium with 400 seating-capacity, two-story research and reference library, and changing exhibition galleries. *The eastern complex contains a round memorial building as well as extensive, permanent exhibition space, consisting of two clusters of galleries that try to evoke the fortress architecture of the region (most evident in a nearby Gurudwara) and form a dramatic silhouette against the surrounding cliff terrain. The gathering of the galleries in groups of five reflects the [[Five Virtues]], a central tenent of Sikhism.
The buildings are constructed of poured-in-place concrete; some beams and columns remain exposed, though a great deal of the structures will be clad in a local honey-colored stone. The rooftops are stainless steel-clad and exhibit a double curvature: they gather and reflect the sky while a series of dams in the ravine create pools that reflect the entire complex at night.<ref>[http://www.msafdie.com/php/print_project.php?id=27 Moshe Safdie and Associates | Project Details ]</ref>
